			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
			
			
			
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="index?page=article&amp;id=00240041052a2b5bb012d44907649037f2&amp;subject_id=0024004102975ad83011b2b83251c0c35">Kevin Belfield, Ranganathan Kumar Named Pegasus Professors</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="index?page=article&amp;id=00240041052a2b5bb012d4490764903985&amp;subject_id=0024004102975ad83011b2b83251c0c35">Students Honored for Academics, Leadership and Service</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="index?page=article&amp;id=00240041052a2b5bb012d44907649037fd&amp;subject_id=0024004102975ad83011b2b83251c0c35">Emeritus Awards: Lifetimes of Distinction</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>The following honors were awarded to UCF faculty members at the annual Founders&rsquo; Day ceremony. Stories on the winners of the Pegasus Professor Awards, professors who were granted emeritus status and students who were awarded Founders&rsquo; Day honors are featured separately.</p>
<p><em><strong>University Award for Excellence in Undergraduate Teaching:</strong></em> <strong>Alisha Janowsky</strong>, College of Sciences. Janowsky, a psychology professor, has one of the largest teaching loads in the department and has taught more courses than any faculty member in recent years. In 2009, she taught nearly 2,150 students in 13 courses. She serves on multiple committees and is also the faculty adviser for UCF&rsquo;s Psychological Society. Most recently, Janowsky was selected as a large class faculty fellow by the Faculty Center for Teaching and Learning, and she will conduct research on the best practices in large class environments.</p>
<p><em>Winners from each college were:</em> Kevin Haran, Lisa Mills, Hakan Ozoglu and Michael Strawser, College of Arts and Humanities; Barbara Moore, College of Business Administration; Timothy R. Blair and Deirdre Englehart, College of Education; C. David Cooper and Christopher D. Geiger, College of Engineering and Computer Science; Alice M. Noblin and Reid M. Oetjen, College of Health and Public Affairs; Tammie J. Kaufman, Rosen College of Hospitality Management; Debopam Chakrabarti, College of Medicine; Kelly Allred, College of Nursing; and Tim Brown, Ann Neville Miller, Kimberly Renk and Rani Vajravelu, College of Sciences.</p>
<p><em><strong>University Award for Excellence in Graduate Teaching:</strong></em> <strong>Avelino J. Gonzalez,</strong> College of Engineering and Computer Science. Gonzalez, a professor in the Department of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science, enhances his graduate courses with the latest developments and trends in the field. A mentor to graduate students, Gonzalez has graduated 10 master&rsquo;s and 10 doctoral students during the past decade. He also was instrumental in establishing and promoting international student exchange programs at UCF, and he currently leads the International Engineering minor.</p>
<p><em>Winners from each college were: </em>Blake Scott, College of Arts and Humanities; Scott M. Waring, College of Education; Thomas A. Bryer, College of Health and Public Affairs; David J. Kwun, Rosen College of Hospitality Management; Diane R. Andrews, College of Nursing; M. G. &ldquo;Jim&rdquo; Moharam, College of Optics and Photonics; and Kimberly Renk, College of Sciences.</p>
<p><em><strong>University Award for Excellence in Research:</strong></em> <strong>Shin-Tson Wu</strong>, College of Optics and Photonics.&nbsp; Wu, an innovator and professor, is a major contributor to the research of liquid crystal displays. His pioneering work helped create technology that is commonly used today in televisions, iPods and cell phones. His work in liquid crystal technology also has led to breakthrough uses of adaptive lenses. He and his research team have obtained more than 70 patents for their work.</p>
<p><em>Winners from each college were:</em> Hakan Ozoglu, College of Arts and Humanities; Carol Saunders, College of Business Administration; Vassiliki Zygouris-Coe, College of Education; Issa Eid Batarseh, College of Engineering and Computer Science; Anthony Pak Hin Kong, College of Health and Public Affairs; Po-Ju Chen, Rosen College of Hospitality Management; Debopam Chakrabarti, College of Medicine; Peter A. Hancock, College of Sciences; and Ming Su, Institutes and Centers.</p>
<p><em><strong>University Awards for Excellence in Faculty Advising: </strong></em><strong>Patricia B. Angley</strong>, College of Arts and Humanities, and <strong>Kristen Schellhase</strong>, College of Health and Public Affairs.</p>
<p>Angley serves as a faculty member and undergraduate adviser for the Department of English. She dedicates great time and effort to the hundreds of students she advises each semester and assists faculty members and chairs in creating new courses and revising the curriculum. She also is the departmental representative on the College of Arts and Humanities Curriculum and Standards Committee.</p>
<p>Schellhase is a faculty member and undergraduate adviser for the Department of Health Professions and the director for UCF&rsquo;s Athletic Training Program. She provides her students with dedicated guidance and accurate information, evidence of her commitment to the success of the students and the program. In addition to her teaching and advising roles, she recruits prospective students and serves as an adviser to the Student Athletic Training Organization.</p>
<p><em><strong>University Award for Excellence in Professional Academic Advising:</strong></em> <strong>Layla Archer,</strong> College of Health and Public Affairs. As assistant director for Undergraduate Student Services, Archer is responsible for retention initiatives and new student orientations in the College of Health and Public Affairs. She designed an outreach web course to engage academic probation students unable to attend a face-to-face workshop.</p>
<p><em><strong>Award for Excellence in Librarianship:</strong></em> <strong>Ying Zhang,</strong> UCF Libraries. An associate librarian, Zhang has improved the library collections with materials that support course curricula, student and faculty research and general knowledge. She has served in several leadership roles statewide. Her expertise has led her to present at conferences and to be featured in the American Library Association publication ALA Cognotes.</p>
<p><em><strong>University Award for Excellence in Professional Service:</strong></em> <strong>Naim Kapucu,</strong> College of Health and Public Affairs. Kapucu&rsquo;s expertise in emergency and crisis management is nationally recognized and led to an invitation to review grant proposal and manuscripts for the National Science Foundation. His work served as a resource for the development of an emergency preparedness paper for former Gov. Charlie Crist. He has organized and chaired numerous panels at national and international conferences, and he is an active member of the American Society of Public Administration, where he founded the Complexity and Network Studies Section.</p>
<p><em><strong>Recognition of Service to the University, 40 Years of Service: </strong></em>Jagdish Chavda, College of Arts and Humanities; Michael C. Hynes, College of Education; and Haven Sweet, College of Sciences.</p>
<p><em><strong>Recognition of Service to the University, 30 Years of Service:</strong></em> Jos&eacute; Fern&aacute;ndez and Robert Rivers, College of Arts and Humanities; Mostafa Bassiouni, Fernando Gomez, Sheau-Dong Lang and Donald C. Malocha, College of Engineering and Computer Science; Michael D. Hampton, Office of Undergraduate Studies; Bill Roach, Division of Research and Commercialization; and Cecelia H. Rivers and Harold A. Utt, Jr., Regional Campuses.</p>
<p><em><strong>Recognition of Service to the University, 20 Years of Service: </strong></em>John C. Hitt, UCF President; Kathleen L. Bell and Robert S. Jones, College of Arts and Humanities; Kathie K. Holland, College of Business Administration; Timothy R. Blair, Kenneth T. Murray and George E. Pawlas, College of Education; Issa Eid Batarseh, Alain Jacques Kassab and Mansooreh Mollaghasemi, College of Engineering and Computer Science; Mary Lou Sole, College of Nursing; and Robert E. Peale and Morgan C. Wang, College of Sciences.</p>
<p><em><strong>Recently Retired and Retiring Faculty:</strong></em> Kristin G. Congdon, Terry Frederick and Roy Pickering, College of Arts and Humanities; Linda Beats Putchinski, College of Business Administration; William Bozeman, Debby Mitchell and George E. Pawlas, College of Education; Ronald D. Dutton, Amar Mukherjee, David Nicholson and George Yeh, College of Engineering and Computer Science; Pamala Griset, College of Health and Public Affairs; Randolph Manning and Loren Nelson, College of Medicine; Jean Kijek, College of Nursing; Richard Gilson, Leslie Sue Lieberman, Peter Panousis and Robert Pritchard, College of Sciences; Gobind H. Atmaram, Division of Research and Commercialization; Jack Webb, Information Technologies and Resources; and Tace Crouse, Office of Undergraduate Studies.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands For Opportunity: </strong>The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 2nd largest in the nation with more than 56,000 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
